00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:32.400
The California constitution of 1850 limited civil participation to whites –

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:37.040
no Asians, no Black people or Native Americans
could vote or testify in court.

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:43.580
Indians were kicked off their land if it had
any mineral value, and thousands of their
orphaned children were sold as slaves.

00:09:43.580 --> 00:09:50.800
And all of this led to the Indian population
of California dropping from 150,000 to about
30,000 between 1848 and 1860.

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:56.240
So it wasn’t at all clear whether California
was the kind of place to be admitted to the
U.S. as a free state or as a slave state.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:02.200
The Missouri Compromise was of no help
here because half of California is below the
36 30 line, and half is above it.

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:10.440
So, a new “Free Soil” party formed in 1848 calling for
the limiting of slavery’s expansion in the west so that
it could be open for white people to live and work.

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:15.040
I just want to be clear that most of the people 
who were for limiting slavery were not, like, un-racist.

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:18.740
So, they nominated the admirably-whiskered
Martin Van Buren for the presidency,

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:25.040
and Van Buren and Democratic nominee
Lewis Cass then split the northern vote, allowing
the aforementioned Zachary Taylor, to win.

00:10:25.040 --> 00:10:30.420
So in 1850, when California finally did ask to be
admitted into the Union, it was as a free state.

00:10:30.420 --> 00:10:37.620
Southerners freaked out because they saw it as
the beginning of the end of slavery, but then, to the rescue came Henry Clay, for his last hurrah.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:41.180
He said, “We can kick this problem down
the road once more”

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:46.960
and brokered a four-part plan that became known
rather anticlimactically as the Compromise of 1850.

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:49.880
Historians, can you name nothing?!
The four points were:

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:52.360
1. California would be admitted as a free
state

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:57.020
2. The slave trade, but not slavery, would
be outlawed in Washington D.C.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:01.000
3. A new, super harsh fugitive slave law would
be enacted, and

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:02.640
4. Popular sovereignty

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:05.600
The idea was that in the remaining
territories taken from Mexico,

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:12.560
the local white inhabitants could decide for
themselves whether the state would be slave or
free when it applied to be part of the U.S.

00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:19.000
Ah, the Compromise of 1850. A great reminder
that nothing protects the rights of minorities
like the tyranny of the majority.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:27.160
There was a huge debate over the bill in which noted asshat John C. Calhoun was so sick that he had to have his pro-slavery, anti-compromise remarks read by a colleague.

00:11:27.160 --> 00:11:34.860
On the other side, New York’s Senator William Seward,
an abolitionist, also argued against compromise, based
on slavery being, you know, wrong.

00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:40.240
But, eventually the compromise did pass, thus
averting a greater crisis for ten whole years.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:45.880
Ralph Waldo Emerson predicted that if the
United States acquired part of Mexico, it
would be like swallowing arsenic.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:48.600
And indeed, arsenic can be a slow-acting poison.

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:53.040
Now I don’t think Ralph Waldo Emerson
was a good enough writer to have thought
that far ahead, but he was right.

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:55.880
